%N A395584 Least k >= 3 such that psi(k)/2 has exactly n divisors, where psi = A002322 is the reduced totient function.
%C A395584 For every n >= 2, psi(2^(n+2)/2) = 2^(n-1) has exactly n divisors, so a(n) <= 2^(n+2).
%C A395584 For prime p, psi(a(p)) must be either 2^p or 2*P^(p-1) for some odd prime P. Since psi(p1^e1 * p2^e2 * ... * pr^er) = lcm(psi(p1^e1), ..., psi(pr^er)), a(p) must actually be a prime power, that is, either 2^(p+2), a prime of the form 2^p + 1 (only possible for p = 2), a prime of the form 2*P^(p-1) + 1, or 3^p. We see that a(p) = 2^(p+2) for p > 3.
%H A395584 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395584/b395584.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..241</a>
%H A395584 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395584/a395584.txt">A395584 on semiprimes <= 10^4</a>.
%H A395584 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395584/a395584.pdf">Notes on A395584</a>.
%H A395584 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395584/a395584_1.txt">PARI Program</a>.
%t A395584 a[n_]:=Module[{k=3}, While[DivisorSigma[0, CarmichaelLambda[k]/2]!=n, k++]; k]; Array[a, 22] (* _James C. McMahon_, Jun 02 2026 *)
